---
import Base from "@layouts/Base.astro"

const origin = Astro.site?.origin || "http://localhost:4321"
const canonical = new URL("/blog/editorial-policy", origin).toString()
const title = "Editorial Policy for Security Guidance | LyraShield AI"
const description =
  "How LyraShield AI researches, reviews, corrects, illustrates, and publishes practical security guidance for builders of AI-built applications."
const reviewedDate = "2026-07-17"
const jsonLd = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "WebPage",
    "@id": canonical,
    name: "How LyraShield AI publishes security guidance",
    description,
    url: canonical,
    dateModified: reviewedDate,
    reviewedBy: { "@id": `${origin}/#organization` },
    isPartOf: { "@id": `${origin}/blog#collection` },
    inLanguage: "en-US",
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "BreadcrumbList",
    itemListElement: [
      { "@type": "ListItem", position: 1, name: "Home", item: `${origin}/` },
      { "@type": "ListItem", position: 2, name: "Blog", item: `${origin}/blog` },
      { "@type": "ListItem", position: 3, name: "Editorial policy", item: canonical },
    ],
  },
]
---

<Base title={title} description={description} canonical={canonical} jsonLd={jsonLd}>
  <article class="editorial-policy">
    <header class="editorial-policy__header">
      <h1>How LyraShield AI publishes security guidance</h1>
      <p>
        This policy explains how the LyraShield Team researches, reviews, illustrates, updates, and
        corrects public security guidance. A polished article is not evidence that a security claim
        is true. The sources, technical review, stated scope, and retained limitations carry that
        responsibility.
      </p>
      <p class="editorial-policy__reviewed">
        Last reviewed: <time datetime={reviewedDate}>July 17, 2026</time>
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="editorial-policy__body">
      <section aria-labelledby="assistance-heading">
        <h2 id="assistance-heading">AI assistance</h2>
        <p>
          AI tools may help organize research, compare an article against its brief, prepare an
          early draft, check internal links, or develop image concepts. They do not approve a
          source, establish a product fact, perform the final technical review, or decide that an
          article is ready to publish.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section aria-labelledby="accountability-heading">
        <h2 id="accountability-heading">Human accountability</h2>
        <p>
          The LyraShield Team remains accountable for every published claim. A reviewer checks the
          cited source, the current repository behavior behind product statements, safe wording,
          examples, limitations, links, metadata, and the final release candidate. Organization
          authorship means the team owns corrections; it is not a claim that one unnamed person has
          tested every system described.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section aria-labelledby="sources-heading">
        <h2 id="sources-heading">Primary sources</h2>
        <p>
          Material technical claims should use standards bodies, government guidance, official
          vulnerability taxonomies, RFCs, vendor documentation, security advisories, or original
          research. Community discussion can reveal reader questions, but it does not establish
          prevalence, product performance, or a security outcome. Editorial inferences are labeled
          as inferences and kept separate from what a source directly establishes.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section aria-labelledby="examples-heading">
        <h2 id="examples-heading">Safe examples and automated-check limits</h2>
        <p>
          Examples use inert code, synthetic accounts, placeholder credentials, and systems the
          tester owns or has permission to assess. We do not publish working exploits against named
          targets. Automated checks are described by the surface and evidence they actually cover.
          A clean result is never presented as proof that an application has no vulnerabilities.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section aria-labelledby="corrections-heading">
        <h2 id="corrections-heading">Corrections and material updates</h2>
        <p>
          We correct factual, technical, and product-boundary errors when they are found. A material
          correction receives a visible update date and an explanatory note when readers need that
          context. Stable URLs and stable heading anchors are preserved whenever possible so cited
          links continue to reach the intended guidance. Editorial cleanup that does not change the
          guidance does not receive a misleading material-update claim.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section aria-labelledby="images-heading">
        <h2 id="images-heading">Image review</h2>
        <p>
          Blog artwork may be generated with Codex Imagegen, then cropped and compressed through a
          deterministic production pipeline. A person reviews the source, central crop, alternate
          text, derivative dimensions, file size, and article fit before approval. Images remain
          text-free and cannot imply customers, certifications, live findings, or security guarantees.
        </p>
      </section>
    </div>

    <footer class="editorial-policy__footer">
      <p>
        Product-specific evidence terms are defined on the <a href="/methodology">methodology page</a>.
        The <a href="/sample-report">sample assurance report</a> is illustrative, not a customer result.
      </p>
    </footer>
  </article>
</Base>

<style>
  .editorial-policy {
    width: min(100% - 2rem, 68rem);
    margin-inline: auto;
    padding-block: clamp(4rem, 9vw, 8rem);
  }

  .editorial-policy__header {
    max-width: 58rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    padding-bottom: clamp(3rem, 7vw, 5rem);
  }

  .editorial-policy h1 {
    max-width: 56rem;
    margin: 0;
    font-family: "Bricolage Grotesque Variable", sans-serif;
    font-size: clamp(3rem, 7vw, 6.5rem);
    font-weight: 800;
    line-height: 0.92;
    letter-spacing: -0.055em;
  }

  .editorial-policy__header > p:not(.editorial-policy__reviewed) {
    max-width: 48rem;
    margin: 2rem 0 0;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    font-size: clamp(1.08rem, 2vw, 1.25rem);
    line-height: 1.75;
  }

  .editorial-policy__reviewed {
    margin: 1.5rem 0 0;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    font-family: "JetBrains Mono Variable", monospace;
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  .editorial-policy__body {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, minmax(0, 1fr));
    column-gap: clamp(2rem, 7vw, 6rem);
  }

  .editorial-policy__body section {
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    padding-block: clamp(2.5rem, 5vw, 4rem);
  }

  .editorial-policy h2 {
    margin: 0;
    font-family: "Bricolage Grotesque Variable", sans-serif;
    font-size: clamp(1.6rem, 3vw, 2.25rem);
    letter-spacing: -0.035em;
  }

  .editorial-policy__body p,
  .editorial-policy__footer p {
    margin: 1rem 0 0;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    line-height: 1.75;
  }

  .editorial-policy a {
    color: var(--color-accent);
    text-underline-offset: 0.2em;
  }

  .editorial-policy a:focus-visible {
    border-radius: 0.2rem;
    outline: 2px solid var(--color-accent);
    outline-offset: 4px;
  }

  .editorial-policy__footer {
    max-width: 48rem;
    padding-top: clamp(2.5rem, 5vw, 4rem);
  }

  @media (max-width: 720px) {
    .editorial-policy__body {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }
  }
</style>
